    15	## Runtime surface
    16	
    17	The canonical runtime verbs available to Python callers are:
    18	
    19	- `Engine.open(...)`
    20	- `engine.write(...)`
    21	- `engine.search(...)`
    22	- `engine.close()`
    23	- `admin.configure(...)`
    24	
    25	`Engine.open(...)` returns the engine handle. The structured open report owned
    26	by `design/engine.md` is accessible after open via `engine.open_report()` (see
    27	Engine-attached instrumentation / control below).
    28	
    29	`Engine.open(path, *, config=None, **engine_config)` accepts the
    30	engine-owned knobs from `design/engine.md` in snake_case:
    31	
    32	- `embedder_pool_size`
    33	- `scheduler_runtime_threads`
    34	- `provenance_row_cap`
    35	- `embedder_call_timeout_ms`
    36	- `slow_threshold_ms`
    37	
    38	The keyword form and `EngineConfig` object form are equivalent. Python
    39	executor usage remains caller-owned and is not an engine config field.
    40	
    41	## Engine-attached instrumentation / control
    42	
    43	These are public instance methods, not extra top-level SDK verbs:
    44	
    45	- `engine.open_report()`
    46	- `engine.drain(timeout_s=...)`
    47	- `engine.counters()`
    48	- `engine.set_profiling(enabled=...)`
    49	- `engine.set_slow_threshold_ms(value=...)`
    50	
    51	Subscriber attachment is provided by:
    52	
    53	- `engine.attach_logging_subscriber(logger, *, heartbeat_interval_ms=None)`
    54	
    55	The helper maps engine events into Python `logging.LogRecord`s with the stable
    56	`fathomdb` payload described by `design/bindings.md`.
    57	
    58	## Caller-visible data shapes
    59	
    60	- `WriteReceipt.cursor`

