     8	---
     9	
    10	# Engine Design
    11	
    12	This file owns the runtime open path, `Engine` lifetime, writer / reader split,
    13	and the concrete meaning of the cursor values surfaced at the public API.
    14	
    15	## Open path
    16	
    17	`Engine.open` owns:
    18	
    19	1. path canonicalization
    20	2. sidecar lock acquisition
    21	3. SQLite open + PRAGMA application
    22	4. always-on corruption detection
    23	5. migration execution
    24	6. embedder identity check
    25	7. embedder warmup
    26	8. writer / scheduler startup
    27	
    28	The detailed step ordering is aligned to HITL `ENG1`; this file is the
    29	authoritative home for the final ordered sequence.
    30	
    31	`Engine.open` runs only the frozen always-on detection subset from HITL `R1`.
    32	0.6.0 exposes no env/config integrity knob at open and does not accept any SDK
    33	config that turns quick/full integrity or round-trip verification on during the
    34	open path.
    35	
    36	The corruption-producing stages are the four `OpenStage` values owned by
    37	`design/errors.md`:
    38	
    39	- `WalReplay` for WAL replay verdicts (`E_CORRUPT_WAL_REPLAY`)
    40	- `HeaderProbe` for page-1/header sanity (`E_CORRUPT_HEADER`)
    41	- `SchemaProbe` for schema / migration-table consistency (`E_CORRUPT_SCHEMA`)
    42	- `EmbedderIdentity` for corrupt stored embedder-profile rows
    43	  (`E_CORRUPT_EMBEDDER_IDENTITY`)
    44	
    45	`E_CORRUPT_INTEGRITY_CHECK` is not an open-path code. That code belongs only to
    46	`doctor check-integrity --full` per `design/recovery.md`.
    47	
    48	## `Engine.open` success result
    49	
    50	On success, `Engine.open` returns the live engine handle plus a structured open
    51	report.
    52	
    53	The canonical success shape is:
    54	
    55	- `engine`
    56	- `report`
    57	
    58	Where `report` carries at least:
    59	
    60	- `schema_version_before`
    61	- `schema_version_after`
    62	- `migration_steps`
    63	- `embedder_warmup_ms`
    64	
    65	Ownership split:
    66	
    67	- `design/migrations.md` owns `schema_version_*` and `migration_steps`
    68	- this file owns the outer "engine handle + report" return contract
    69	- `design/embedder.md` owns the semantics of warmup itself; this file owns the
    70	  fact that `embedder_warmup_ms` is surfaced as part of open success
    71	
    72	On migration failure, no engine handle is returned. The typed `MigrationError`
    73	instead carries the migration-owned failure report described in
    74	`design/migrations.md`.
    75	
    76	## Writer / reader split
    77	
    78	- One dedicated writer thread owns the only write connection.
    79	- Reader connections are pooled and never serialize behind one connection.
    80	- `admin.configure` is writer-thread work. It is not a side path and does not
    81	  bypass the same lock, migration, or error rules as normal writes.
    82	
    83	## `PreparedWrite::AdminSchema` provenance
    84	
    85	`PreparedWrite::AdminSchema(AdminSchemaWrite)` exists because
    86	`admin.configure` is already accepted public surface in 0.6.0 and its DDL work
    87	must travel through the same writer-thread machinery as every other state
    88	change. The variant is not speculative extension surface and must not be
    89	deleted as "future admin work."
    90	
    91	Why it exists:
    92	
    93	- `admin.configure` is a top-level SDK verb under REQ-053.
    94	- AC-003c and AC-021 already require observable admin work on the canonical
    95	  engine path.
    96	- ADR-0.6.0-prepared-write-shape commits to one typed carrier enum for writer
    97	  submissions; admin DDL therefore needs an engine-side representation inside
    98	  that carrier.
    99	
   100	Status in 0.6.0:
   101	
   102	- The existence of the `AdminSchema` variant is locked for 0.6.0.
   103	- The exact field set of `AdminSchemaWrite` remains owned here and by the
   104	  interface docs. It is still an internal engine carrier, not a promise that
   105	  callers directly construct arbitrary DDL payloads.
   106	
   107	## Canonical identity and supersession
   108	
   109	Folded 2026-05-12 from archived `design-detailed-supersession.md` +
   110	`design-id-generation-policy.md` per the Phase 1a learnings disposition
   111	(`learnings.md:94, 98`). This section is the authoritative home for the
   112	0.6.0 canonical identity contract.
   113	
   114	### Identity model
   115	
   116	Canonical rows separate physical row identity from logical entity identity:
   117	
   118	- `row_id` — identifies one physical version of a node, edge, chunk, run,
   119	  step, or action. Globally unique.
   120	- `logical_id` — identifies the application entity across versions. Stable
   121	  across supersessions. Required on `NodeInsert` and `EdgeInsert`; chunk /
   122	  run / step / action use the single `id` field which is both physical and
   123	  logical (these row kinds are not superseded in 0.6.0).
   124	- The **active** version is the row for a given `logical_id` whose
   125	  `superseded_at IS NULL`.
   126	- A partial unique index enforces at most one active row per `logical_id`
   127	  per kind.
   128	
   129	Edges reference logical identities; traversals resolve to the current
   130	active endpoint at read time.
   131	
   132	### ID generation policy
   133	
   134	Caller-owned IDs. The engine does not generate, assign, or sequence IDs as
   135	part of the write path:
   136	
   137	- Callers MUST provide `row_id` and `logical_id` on every `NodeInsert` and
   138	  `EdgeInsert`.
   139	- Callers MUST provide `id` on every `ChunkInsert`, `RunInsert`,
   140	  `StepInsert`, and `ActionInsert`.
   141	- Empty or duplicate-within-request IDs are rejected at `prepare_write`
   142	  validation as a `WriteValidationError`, not at SQLite execution time.
   143	- Cross-request uniqueness violations surface as the typed SQLite-mapped
   144	  error per `design/errors.md`.
   145	
   146	Rationale: caller-owned IDs preserve idempotent replay, keep the engine
   147	stateless for ID sequencing, and let supersession address rows by stable
   148	`logical_id` without a query round-trip.
   149	
   150	The engine ships a standalone `new_id() -> String` utility (26-character
   151	ULID) for callers that lack their own ID scheme. The utility is not part
   152	of the write path; callers with existing identifiers do not need it.
   153	
   154	### Write semantics under supersession
   155	
   156	Each accepted batch executes one SQLite transaction (see "Batch submission
   157	semantics" below). Within that transaction, supersession proceeds as:
   158	
   159	1. Validate canonical rows and references.
   160	2. Append new physical rows (nodes, edges, chunks, runs, steps, actions).
   161	3. For each replaced `logical_id`, mark the prior active row superseded
   162	   (`superseded_at = <commit timestamp>`); do NOT mutate the prior row's
   163	   value columns.
   164	4. Enqueue derived-projection invalidation for affected logical ids and
   165	   kinds (FTS rows for retired chunks, vector rows for retired nodes).
   166	5. Commit, or roll the entire batch back.
   167	
   168	Supersession preserves both the old and the new physical row as separate
   169	facts. The old row is marked inactive; its content is not rewritten.
   170	
   171	### Restoration as a canonical write
   172	
   173	"Restore a `logical_id`" means making a previously superseded physical row
   174	active again. The 0.6.0 restoration operator (`Engine::restore_logical_id`,
   175	recovery-only — see `design/recovery.md`) appends a new active row that
   176	preserves restore provenance rather than mutating the historical
   177	`superseded_at` column. The replay source is the op-store
   178	`append_only_log` write history for the logical id (see
   179	`design/recovery.md § Logical-id purge and restore`).
   180	
   181	### Projection invariants
   182	
   183	Projections follow canonical active state:
   184	
   185	- FTS rows derive from active chunks; supersession retires the
   186	  corresponding FTS row.
   187	- Per-kind vector rows (`vec_<kind>`) derive from active nodes;
   188	  supersession retires the corresponding vector row.
   189	- A canonical row whose `superseded_at IS NOT NULL` has no derived
   190	  projection rows for that logical id and kind.
   191	
   192	Recovery tooling (`recover --rebuild-projections`, `--rebuild-vec0`)
   193	rebuilds projections from the active canonical state, not from history.
   194	
   195	## Batch submission semantics
   196	
   197	`Engine.write(&[PreparedWrite])` is one ordered writer submission in 0.6.0.
   198	
   199	The contract is:
   200	
   201	1. The slice is validated as one batch before commit-sensitive work begins.
   202	2. If any element fails save-time validation, the batch is rejected and no
   203	   SQLite write transaction commits any member of the batch.
   204	3. If validation succeeds, the writer executes the batch in caller order inside
   205	   one SQLite transaction.
   206	4. Mixed canonical rows and op-store rows in the same slice commit atomically.
   207	5. One write cursor `c_w` is allocated for the committed batch as a whole, not
   208	   per element.
   209	6. Projection work derived from committed writes is enqueued only after that
   210	   transaction commits.
   211	
   212	0.6.0 does not regroup the slice by variant, split one slice into multiple
   213	transactions, or expose partial-success semantics. The caller-visible contract
   214	is "all committed at one cursor or none committed."
   215	
   216	`admin.configure` uses the same writer machinery and transactional rules, but
   217	it is a separate public verb from `write`; this file does not widen REQ-053
   218	into a promise that arbitrary mixed admin-and-data batches are first-class user
   219	surface.
   220	

